Gathering Data¶

The three sources come from a csv file, tsv file, and twitter_api.py

Twitter Archive¶

In [4]:
# Import the Twitter archive CSV file into a DataFrame
arc_df = pd.read_csv('twitter-archive-enhanced.csv')

Image Predictions¶

In [5]:
# Download tweet image predictions TSV using the Requests library and write it to image_predictions.tsv
url = 'https://d17h27t6h515a5.cloudfront.net/topher/2017/August/599fd2ad_image-predictions/image-predictions.tsv'
response = requests.get(url)
# Create file
with open('image_predictions.tsv', mode='wb') as file:
    file.write(response.content)
    
# Import the tweet image predictions TSV file into a DataFrame
img_df = pd.read_csv('image_predictions.tsv', sep='\t')

In [15]:
# Make file if it doesn't already exist
file_name = 'tweet_json.txt'
if not os.path.isfile(file_name):
    open(file_name, 'w').close()
In [16]:
tweet_ids = arc_df.tweet_id
In [17]:
tweet_errors = {}
tweet_count = 1
data = []
for tweet_id in tweet_ids:
    try:
        # Print id counter
        print(tweet_count)
        # Collect tweet info
        tweet = api.get_status(tweet_id, tweet_mode='extended')
        info = tweet._json
        #print(info) # debug test
        #break # debug test
        # Append to file
        data.append(info)
        with open(file_name, 'w') as file:
            json.dump(data, file)
        # Print timer info to estimate time until wake-up
        print(datetime.datetime.now().time())
        # Add one to the tweet count for further printing
        tweet_count += 1
        
    except Exception as e:
        # Print exception info and add to tweet_errors dict
        print(str(tweet_id) + ": " + str(e))
        tweet_errors[str(tweet_count - 1) + "_" + str(tweet_id)] = info

In [18]:
data = {}
data['tweets'] = []
tweet_errors = {}
tweet_count = 1
for tweet_id in tweet_ids:
    try:
        # Print id counter
        print(tweet_count)
        # Collect tweet info
        tweet = api.get_status(tweet_id, tweet_mode='extended')
        info = tweet._json
        # Collect specific data
        retweet_count = info['retweet_count']
        favorite_count = info['favorite_count']
        followers_count = info['user']['followers_count']
        # Append to data dict
        data['tweets'].append({
            'tweet_id': tweet_id, 
            'retweet_count': retweet_count, 
            'favorite_count': favorite_count,
            'followers_count': followers_count
        })
        #print(retweet_count, favorite_count, followers_count) # debug test
        #print(data)
        #break # debug test
        # Print timer info to estimate time until wake-up
        print(datetime.datetime.now().time())
        # Add one to the tweet count for further printing
        tweet_count += 1
        
    except Exception as e:
        # Print exception info and add to tweet_errors dict
        print(str(tweet_count) + "_" + str(tweet_id) + ": " + str(e))
        tweet_errors[str(tweet_count) + "_" + str(tweet_id)] = info

In [19]:
# Extract data from file
df_list = []
with open('tweet_json.txt') as json_file:
    data = json.load(json_file)
    for tweet in data:
        df_list.append({'tweet_id': tweet['id'],
                        'retweet_count': tweet['retweet_count'], 
                        'favorite_count': tweet['favorite_count'],
                        'followers_count': tweet['user']['followers_count']})
In [20]:
# Create DataFrame from list of dictionaries
api_data = pd.DataFrame(df_list, columns = ['tweet_id', 
                                            'retweet_count', 
                                            'favorite_count', 
                                            'followers_count'])

img_df (tweet image predictions) columns:

  • tweet_id: the unique identifier for each tweet
  • jpg_url: dog's image URL
  • img_num: the image number that corresponded to the most confident prediction - (numbered 1 to 4 since tweets can have up to four images)
  • p1: algorithm's #1 prediction for the image in the tweet
  • p1_conf: how confident the algorithm is in its #1 prediction
  • p1_dog: whether or not the #1 prediction is a breed of dog
  • p2: algorithm's #2 prediction for the image in the tweet
  • p2_conf: how confident the algorithm is in its #2 prediction
  • p2_dog: whether or not the #2 prediction is a breed of dog
  • p3: algorithm's #3 prediction for the image in the tweet
  • p3_conf: how confident the algorithm is in its #3 prediction
  • p3_dog: whether or not the #3 prediction is a breed of dog

status_df (tweet status) columns:

  • id: the unique identifier for each tweet
  • retweet_count: number of times this Tweet has been retweeted
  • favorite_count: indicates approximately how many times this Tweet has been liked by Twitter users
  • display_text_range: an array of two unicode code point indices, identifying the inclusive start and exclusive end of the displayable content of the Tweet

Data inclusion Criteria¶

  • Do not include retweets
  • Only tweets that have images
  • Do not include replies

Findings¶

Quality¶

arc_df table¶

  • contains retweets and therefore, duplicates
  • numerous tweet_id(s) of arc_df table are missing in img_df table
  • rating_numerator has values less than 10 with large numbers
  • rating_denomintaor has values other than 10
  • some dog names start with lowercase / idenified as not names(a, an)
  • some have more than one dog stage
  • Replies are included in the dataset
  • text column contains both text and short version of link

img_df table¶

  • the lower number of entries indicates that some posts do not have images
  • erroneous datatype (tweet_id)
  • rop ducplicated jpg_url.
  • p1, p2 and p3 have unccessary underscore instead of space
  • p1, p2 and p3 have inconsistent capital words

api_df table¶

  • erroneous dataype (tweet_id)
  • retweet and favorite info is not available for all tweets
  • the data is separate from the other tweet data

Tidiness¶

arc_df table¶
  • doggo, floofer, pupper and puppo columns in arc_df table should be merged into one column named "stage" ##### img_df table
  • Multiple columns contains the same type of data ##### api_data table
  • It is separate fromt the other tweet data

Cleaning Data¶

In [55]:
# Take a copy of arc_df on which the cleaning tasks will be performed
arc_df_clean = arc_df.copy()
img_df_clean = img_df.copy()
api_data_clean = api_data.copy()

Missing Data¶

  1. Missing counts for doggo, floofer, pupper and puppo
  2. Missing names
  3. Second name missing
MIssing counts for doggo, floofer, puppter and puppo in arc_df¶

Nulls represents "None" for doggo, floofer, pupper, and puppo

In [58]:
def find_dog_type(df, dog_type):
    dog_list = []
    for row in df['text']:
        if dog_type in row:
            dog_list.append(dog_type)
        else:
            dog_list.append(np.NaN)
    return dog_list

Missing Names idenitifed from text in name in arc_table¶
Define: Create function to identify pet names¶

Pet names are less than 10 characeters but more than 2, and it is capitalized.

In [67]:
def find_names(df):
    name_list = []
    for row in df['text']:
        # Find first "."
        first_period = row.find(".")
        # If no period is found, assume there is no name
        if first_period == -1:
            name_list.append(np.NaN)
        else:
            # Find word before period
            word_before = row[:first_period].rsplit(' ', 1)[-1]
            # Check if word is capitalized
            if word_before == word_before.title():
                # Add exclusionary criteria - not more than 10 letters, not less than 2 letters, not in other_words, only alphanumeric
                other_words = ["This", "Xbox", "Oh", "Christmas", "Up", "Pupper", "Doggo", "Puppo", "Floofer"]
                if (len(word_before) > 10) or any(word in word_before for word in other_words) or any(c for c in word_before if c not in string.ascii_letters + "'") or (len(word_before) < 2):
                    name_list.append(np.NaN)
                else:
                    name_list.append(word_before)
            else:
                name_list.append(np.NaN)
        
    return name_list
In [68]:
name_list = find_names(arc_df_clean)
arc_df_clean.name = name_list

arc_df_clean['timestamp'] = pd.to_datetime(arc_df_clean['timestamp'])
arc_df_clean['date'] = arc_df_clean['timestamp'].apply(lambda time: time.strftime('%m-%d-%Y'))
arc_df_clean['time'] = arc_df_clean['timestamp'].apply(lambda time: time.strftime('%H:%M'))

Define: Values for rating_denominator are incorrect¶

In [133]:
# regex to match fractions
pattern = "\s*(\d+([.]\d+)?([/]\d+))"

# function which will match the above pattern and return an array of fractions, if any
def tokens(x):
  return [m.group(1) for m in re.finditer(pattern, x)]
In [136]:
# iterate through all those records whose rating_denominator is not 10
for i, row in arc_df_clean[arc_df_clean.rating_denominator != 10].iterrows():
    d = row.rating_denominator
    
    # if rating_denominator is greater than 10 and divisible by 10
    if d > 10 and d%10 == 0:
        # assign divisor as the quotient
        divisor = d/10
        n = row.rating_numerator
        
        # if rating_numerator is greater than 10 and divisible by the divisor
        if n%divisor == 0:
            # reassign rating_denominator as 10
            arc_df_clean.set_value(i, 'rating_denominator', 10)
            # reassign rating_numerator as the quotient of rating_numerator by divisor
            arc_df_clean.set_value(i, 'rating_numerator', int(n/divisor))
    
    # for all those records whose rating_denominator is either less than 10 or not divisible by 10
    else:
        # extract all fractions(ratings) from text using tokens function
        ratings = tokens(row.text)
        # iterate through all the fractions
        for rating in ratings:
            # if denominator of any such fraction is equal to 10
            if rating.split('/')[1] == '10':
                # reassign rating_denominator as 10
                arc_df_clean.set_value(i, 'rating_denominator', 10)
                # reassign rating_numerator as the numerator value of this fraction
                arc_df_clean.set_value(i, 'rating_numerator', int(round(float(rating.split('/')[0]))))
                break

plt.savefig('ret_fav')
